{"semantic":{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part01228","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"slipware"},"scopeNote":{"en":"A general term for wares decorated predominantly with one or more clay slips of greater or lesser iron content than the body clay. The slip clays fire to a contrasting color or shade from that of the body. Slipware can be decorated by pouring, dipping, painting, daubing or trailing slips on to the unfired, or sometimes once-fired, body. After it is applied, the slip can be manipulated by twisting the piece, by combing or feathering the slip into more regular designs or, after drying to a tacky consistency, can be carved in the sgraffito technique. Dipping, trailing, and marbling are other common techniques used for slip-decorated ceramics. The application of slip almost always precedes glazing."},"broader":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00224","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"pottery (object genre)"}}],"broaderTransitive":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00224","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"pottery (object genre)"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00064","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Keramik","no":"keramikk","sv":"keramik","fi":"keramiikka","pt":"cerâmica","en":"ceramics","hr":"keramika","it":"ceramica","fr":"céramique","hu":"kerámia","es":"cerámica","cs":"keramika","sl":"keramika","pl":"ceramika","ca":"ceràmica","nl":"keramiek"},"altLabel":{"en":["ceramics (objects)"]}}],"inCollections":["http://partage.vocnet.org/NonIndexingConcepts"],"exactMatch":["http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300264955"],"inSchemes":["http://partage.vocnet.org/Objects"],"vocabulary":{"name":"partageplus","version":"0"}}}

{"semantic":{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part01234","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"gestochen (Druckvorgang)","en":"engraving (printing process)","hr":"graviranje"},"altLabel":{"de":["gestochen (Druckplatte)"]},"scopeNote":{"en":"The intaglio process in which the design is incised into a printing plate, usually a flat copper plate, with the aid of a graver or burin that is held in the palm of the hand and pushed against the copper to cut lines comprising V-shaped grooves. The plate is then inked up, wiped so that ink is retained in the grooves and then forced out under the pressure of the printing process to create lines on the paper. The technique was first developed in the early 15th century in Germany, probably by goldsmiths who wished to keep records of the designs they had engraved on their wares. The process is distinct from \"wood engraving (process),\" which is a process for relief printing; \"wood cut (process)\" refers to engraving wood blocks for printing. Historically, \"engraving\" has sometimes been used incorrectly to refer to all printmaking processes, particulalry any process employing printing plates. For the single step of incising an inscription or design into any surface, not only a printing plate, see \"engraving (action).\""},"inCollections":["http://partage.vocnet.org/IndexingConcepts","http://partage.vocnet.org/PPTechnique"],"exactMatch":["http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300053225"],"inSchemes":["http://partage.vocnet.org/Activities"],"vocabulary":{"name":"partageplus","version":"0"}}}

Lace may be made with a needle or with bobbins. Embroidery may be added. Modern lace may be made by machine. Openwork fabrics made on a loom and ornamental openwork knitting are generally not classified as lace. Lace is often white or monochromatic. True lace developed in the fourteenth century in Europe and the Middle East, although ornamented openwork fabrics were known in ancient cultures, including the Egyptian culture. {"semantic":{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00263","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Gusseisen","fi":"valurauta","sv":"gjutjärn","pt":"ferro fundido","en":"cast iron","hr":"lijevano željezo"},"scopeNote":{"en":"An iron alloy containing about 2 to 4% carbon and 1 to 3% silicon, having a high compressive strength but low tensile strength. Cast iron is manufactured by melting scrap iron or pig iron in a cupola that is in contact with the coal fuel, then casting the molten iron into a mold. A large range of building and decorative items are made of cast iron by pouring the molten metal into sand molds and then machining. It is inexpensive and easy to make. It was made in China by at least the 3rd century BCE; the technique for its production did not reach Europe until medieval times."},"broader":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00261","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"iron alloy"}}],"broaderTransitive":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00261","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"iron alloy"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00259","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Metall","sv":"metall","fi":"metalli","pt":"metal","en":"metal","hr":"metal"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00229","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"materials (matter)"}}],"inCollections":["http://partage.vocnet.org/IndexingConcepts","http://partage.vocnet.org/PPMaterial"],"exactMatch":["http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300011004"],"inSchemes":["http://partage.vocnet.org/Materials"],"vocabulary":{"name":"partageplus","version":"0"}}}

{"semantic":{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00590","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Beton","sv":"betong","fi":"betoni","pt":"betão","en":"concrete","hr":"beton"},"scopeNote":{"en":"A hard, strong construction material comprising a mixture of sand, gravel, crushed rock, or other aggregate, held together, typically by a hardened paste of cement and\\/or lime. Several types of aggregate are used such as crushed stone, slag, cinders or gravel. Ancient Romans developed pozzolan cement about the 3rd century BCE. Modern concretes use various cements such as portland or hydraulic. Concrete is durable and relatively inexpensive, used for foundations, bridges, dams, walls, and highways. Concrete is strong in compression but weak in tension so it is often reinforced with steel bars or wire netting. Once a concrete mixture is stirred with water and poured into a mold, it is allowed to cure slowly over about a week. Stresses, such as vibration, freezing, and rapid drying, will diminish the strength and durability of the concrete. As it ages, concrete is subject to erosion, spalling, and pollution. Poor mixing can cause erosion. Spalling can be due to freeze-thaw cycles of moisture and ice, salt crystallization, or corrosion of steel reinforcements. Acid rain can deplete the natural alkaline reserve of fresh concrete."},"broader":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00229","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"materials (matter)"}}],"broaderTransitive":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00229","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"materials (matter)"}}],"inCollections":["http://partage.vocnet.org/IndexingConcepts","http://partage.vocnet.org/PPMaterial"],"exactMatch":["http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300010737"],"inSchemes":["http://partage.vocnet.org/Materials"],"vocabulary":{"name":"partageplus","version":"0"}}}
{"semantic":{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part01209","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Linde","en":"linden (wood)","hr":"lipa"},"altLabel":{"en":["limewood (wood)"]},"scopeNote":{"en":"Light-brown wood from of any of several trees of the genus Tilia, having a straight grain and easily worked. Linden wood is used for furniture and cabinets. Its particular structural character lends itself well to carving, allowing tools to be used both along the grain and to some extent axially. Because linden wood is soft and workable, it has been used since the 1500s for decorative items with intricate carvings, such as picture frames and sculptures. Despite its relative cost, it was the most common wood used for sculpture in Germany. During the late 15th and early 16th centuries limewood was the preferred material for the genre of the winged altarpiece."},"broader":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00606","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"hardwood"}}],"broaderTransitive":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00606","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"hardwood"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00295","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Holz","sv":"trä","fi":"puu","pt":"madeira","en":"wood","hr":"drvo"},"altLabel":{"en":["wood (plant material)"]}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00297","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"plant material"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00229","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"materials (matter)"}}],"inCollections":["http://partage.vocnet.org/IndexingConcepts","http://partage.vocnet.org/PPMaterial"],"exactMatch":["http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300012456"],"inSchemes":["http://partage.vocnet.org/Materials"],"vocabulary":{"name":"partageplus","version":"0"}}}

{"semantic":{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00885","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Öldruck","fi":"öljypainokuvat","sv":"oljetryck","pt":"cópia a óleo","en":"oil prints","hr":"uljni tisak"},"altLabel":{"de":["Öldrucke"]},"scopeNote":{"en":"Hand-inked photographs produced by a bichromate process developed by G.E.H. Rawlins ca. 1904. A sheet of paper is coated with a thin layer of gelatin and sensitized with bichromate, dried in the dark and exposed under a negative. Exposure hardens the gelatin in the shadow areas and partially in mid-tones. Soaking in water subsequently removes sensitizer and causes the mid-tone and highlight areas to absorb moisture. Oil based inks are repelled in these areas, and remain to a greater or lesser degree in others. The plate is then allowed to dry or is transfer-printed to another sheet, then re-inked for more prints."},"broader":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00921","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"pigment prints"}}],"narrower":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00876","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Bromöldruck","sv":"bromoljetryck","fi":"bromivedos","pt":"bromoil","en":"bromoil prints","hr":"bromouljni tisak"},"altLabel":{"de":["Bromöldrucke"]}}],"broaderTransitive":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00921","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"pigment prints"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00917","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"photographic prints"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00918","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"positives (photographs)"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00419","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Fotografie","no":"fotografi","fi":"valokuvat","sv":"fotografier","pt":"fotografia","en":"photographs","hr":"fotografije","it":"fotografie","fr":"photographie","hu":"fénykép","es":"fotografías","cs":"fotografie","sl":"fotografije","pl":"fotografie","ca":"fotografies","nl":"foto's"},"altLabel":{"de":["Fotos","Fotografien","Photographien","Photographie"],"pt":["fotografias"]}}],"inCollections":["http://partage.vocnet.org/IndexingConcepts","http://partage.vocnet.org/PPRefiningObjectType"],"exactMatch":["http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300138319"],"inSchemes":["http://partage.vocnet.org/Objects"],"vocabulary":{"name":"partageplus","version":"0"}}}

{"semantic":{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00226","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Majolika","no":"majolika","fi":"majolika","sv":"majolika","pt":"majólica","en":"maiolica","hr":"majolika","it":"maioliche","fr":"majolique","hu":"majolika","es":"mayólica","cs":"majolika","sl":"majolika","pl":"majolika","nl":"majolica","ca":"majòlica"},"altLabel":{"sl":["posodje iz majolike"]},"scopeNote":{"en":"Refers to tin-glazed earthenware, particularly such ware produced in Italy. The term originally referred to the island of Majorca (or an alternate theory has it referring to Malaga), and designated only Hispano-Moresque lusterware; but since the 16th century it has been used to refer to Italian tin-glazed ware and imitations of the Italian ware. It is characterized by painted decoration of high quality executed in several colors on the dry but unfired tin glaze, generally with a final coating of clear lead glaze. The range of colors is typically limited to cobalt blue, copper green, manganese purple, antimony yellow, and iron red, with white provided by the tin-glaze material. When white is used for painting, it is applied onto a bluish-white glaze or blue ground. The luster is typically a golden color derived from silver or a mother-of-pearl effect."},"broader":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00223","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Irdenware","no":"leirgods","sv":"lergods","fi":"savitavara","pt":"louça de barro","en":"earthenware","hr":"glineno posuđe","it":"terracotta","fr":"faïence","hu":"agyagkerámia","es":"loza","cs":"pórovina","sl":"lončenina","pl":"wyroby garncarskie","ca":"pisa","nl":"aardewerk"},"altLabel":{"de":["Töpferware"]}}],"broaderTransitive":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00223","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Irdenware","no":"leirgods","sv":"lergods","fi":"savitavara","pt":"louça de barro","en":"earthenware","hr":"glineno posuđe","it":"terracotta","fr":"faïence","hu":"agyagkerámia","es":"loza","cs":"pórovina","sl":"lončenina","pl":"wyroby garncarskie","ca":"pisa","nl":"aardewerk"},"altLabel":{"de":["Töpferware"]}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00064","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Keramik","no":"keramikk","sv":"keramik","fi":"keramiikka","pt":"cerâmica","en":"ceramics","hr":"keramika","it":"ceramica","fr":"céramique","hu":"kerámia","es":"cerámica","cs":"keramika","sl":"keramika","pl":"ceramika","ca":"ceràmica","nl":"keramiek"},"altLabel":{"en":["ceramics (objects)"]}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00224","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"pottery (object genre)"}}],"inCollections":["http://partage.vocnet.org/IndexingConcepts","http://partage.vocnet.org/PPObjectType"],"exactMatch":["http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300021170"],"inSchemes":["http://partage.vocnet.org/Objects","http://partage.vocnet.org/MicroObjectTypes"],"vocabulary":{"name":"partageplus","version":"0"}}}

{"semantic":{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part01015","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Manufaktur","sv":"manufakturer","fi":"valmistaja","pt":"manufactura","en":"manufactories","hr":"manufaktura"},"altLabel":{"de":["Manufakturen"],"en":["manufactory"]},"scopeNote":{"en":"Refers to organized groups who make objects primarily by hand. In the context of Western art and decorative arts, the term \"manufactory\" is often used rather than \"factory (organization)\" to distinguish groups active in the 17th century or later that made fine art, furniture, tapestries, ceramics, and other decorative objects, as contrasted to workers active in modern industrial complexes, or \"factories (structures),\" where objects other than art are produced. Manufactories are typically characterized by the types of objects they produce, by the relatively large numbers of artists and craftsmen employed, and by the relatively complex administrative structure of director, or \"directeur,\" and several masters, who may each supervise a separate workshop or studio of artisans and apprentices. Manufactories were often sponsored by a monarch or other powerful person. For smaller groups consisting of a master artist or architect and his or her assistants or pupils, especially those dating from the mid-17th century on, use \"studios (organizations).\" For smaller groups of artists or craftsmen collaborating to produce works, often under a master's name, especially when the groups existed prior to the 17th century, use \"workshops (organizations).\""},"broader":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00551","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"organisations"},"altLabel":{"en":["organizations (groups)"]}}],"broaderTransitive":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00551","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"organisations"},"altLabel":{"en":["organizations (groups)"]}}],"inCollections":["http://partage.vocnet.org/IndexingConcepts","http://partage.vocnet.org/PPRoleActor"],"exactMatch":["http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300264603"],"inSchemes":["http://partage.vocnet.org/Agents"],"vocabulary":{"name":"partageplus","version":"0"}}}

Gouache paints use opaque pigments rather than the transparent pigments used in watercolor paints. Chalk and other white fillers may be added to some colors. Gouache was used for miniature paintings in the 16th-18th centuries, for decorative paintings on interior walls, and for printing wall paper patterns. Poster paints are an inexpensive version of gouache. The term is most often associated with three-dimensional objects that are functional: furniture, buildings, and machines, and less often with painting, drawing, or sculpture. Usage is extended to paintings and drawings to describe conceptual affinities, rather than discrete objects. Use \"prototypes\" to describe sculpture only if the works conform to other completed works in size, shape, and detail. For small-scale three dimensional renderings for sculpture, use \"maquettes,\" and for more finely detailed sketches for sculpture or painting, use \"bozzetti.\""},"inCollections":["http://partage.vocnet.org/IndexingConcepts","http://partage.vocnet.org/PPRefiningObjectType"],"exactMatch":["http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300166391"],"inSchemes":["http://partage.vocnet.org/Objects"],"vocabulary":{"name":"partageplus","version":"0"}}}

Early pieces were often simply a board on legs placed near the dining table. By the 17th century sideboards were being designed with a cupboard or drawers beneath a flat table surface. The top was higher than a standard table, allowing the plate on display to be seen easily, as well as making the food more conveniently accessible to a standing person. {"semantic":{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00274","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Bronze","fi":"pronssi","sv":"brons","pt":"bronze","en":"bronze","hr":"bronca"},"altLabel":{"en":["bronze (metal)"]},"scopeNote":{"en":"Refers to a broad range of alloys of copper, specifically any non-ferrous alloy of copper, tin, and zinc or other trace metals. Bronze was made before 3,000 BCE -- possibly as early as 10,000 BCE, although its common use in tools and decorative items is dated only in later artifacts. The proportions of copper and tin vary widely, from 70 to 95 percent copper in surviving ancient artifacts. Because of the copper base, bronze may be very malleable and easy to work. By the Middle Ages in Europe, it was recognized that using the metals in certain proportions could yield specific properties. Some modern bronzes contain no tin at all, substituting other metals such as aluminum, manganese, and even zinc. Historically, the term was used interchangeably with \"latten.\" U.S. standard bronze is composed of 90% copper, 7% tin and 3% zinc. Ancient bronze alloys sometimes contained up to 14% tin."},"broader":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00272","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"copper alloy"}}],"broaderTransitive":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00272","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"copper alloy"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00265","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"nonferrous metal"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00259","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Metall","sv":"metall","fi":"metalli","pt":"metal","en":"metal","hr":"metal"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00229","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"materials (matter)"}}],"inCollections":["http://partage.vocnet.org/IndexingConcepts","http://partage.vocnet.org/PPMaterial"],"exactMatch":["http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300010957"],"inSchemes":["http://partage.vocnet.org/Materials"],"vocabulary":{"name":"partageplus","version":"0"}}}

In the context of textiles and needleworking, its meaning overlaps with \"sewing.\" In the context of bookbinding, it refers to the fastening together a number of leaves or gatherings by passing the thread or wire through all of the sheets at once; it is distinct from \"sewing,\" which, in the context of bookbinding, is used for the joining of leaves or gatherings together one by one by drawing thread or wire backwards and forwards through the back fold of each sheet to attach it to the cords."},"inCollections":["http://partage.vocnet.org/IndexingConcepts","http://partage.vocnet.org/PPTechnique"],"exactMatch":["http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300053660"],"inSchemes":["http://partage.vocnet.org/Activities"],"vocabulary":{"name":"partageplus","version":"0"}}}

{"semantic":{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00489","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Knochen","sv":"ben","fi":"luu","pt":"osso","en":"bone","hr":"kost"},"altLabel":{"de":["Gebein"],"en":["bone (material)"]},"scopeNote":{"en":"The rigid, calcareous material that is white in color and forms the skeleton of vertebrates; primarily composed of calcium hydroxyapatite with smaller amounts of calcium carbonate, calcium fluoride, magnesium phosphate, and ossein, a high molecular weight protein. Bones have a concentric structure with central lymphatic canals surrounded by a spongy lamellar region protected by a dense outer cortex. Bone has been carved and used since ancient times for many purposes, including fish-hooks, spear heads, needles, handles, and art objects. Bones were also burnt to produce bone black and boiled to produce bone glue. It was originally developed by Staffordshire potters, who were experimenting to find a substitute for Chinese porcelain. Around 1750 they created a a fine white earthenware with a rich yellowish glaze; the ware had a light body and clean glaze, making it desirable for domestic ware. At the time, the cream color was considered a fault; as an improvement, Wedgwood introduced a white to bluish white product called \"pearlware\" in 1779. It was produced for nearly a century. {"semantic":{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00191","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Monstranz","fi":"monstranssit","ru":"monstranser","pt":"custódia","en":"monstrances","hr":"pokaznica"},"altLabel":{"de":["Monstranzen"],"hr":["monstanca"]},"scopeNote":{"en":"Christian liturgical vessels in which the Host (the bread consecrated in the Eucharist) may be displayed through an opening or through a transparent material; used either on an altar or in processions. It is usually made of gold or silver and is often decorated with precious stones. From the Baroque period onwards the Host is typically surrounded by a sunburst design. Modern usage has limited the meaning to vessels intended for the exposition of the Host; however the term was originally applied to all kinds of vessels of goldsmith's or silversmith's work in which glass or crystal were used to allow the contents to be readily visible, whether the contents were the Host, a relic of a saint, or another object. Distinguished from \"pyxes,\" which are vessels used to hold the reserved Host on the altar or to carry the Eucharist to the sick."},"broader":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00193","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Zeremonialgefäß","fi":"rituaaliastiat","sv":"ceremoniella behållare","pt":"recipientes cerimoniais","en":"ceremonial containers","hr":"spremnica (ceremonijalna)"},"altLabel":{"de":["Kultgerät","Ritualgerät","Liturgisches Gerät"]}}],"broaderTransitive":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00193","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Zeremonialgefäß","fi":"rituaaliastiat","sv":"ceremoniella behållare","pt":"recipientes cerimoniais","en":"ceremonial containers","hr":"spremnica (ceremonijalna)"},"altLabel":{"de":["Kultgerät","Ritualgerät","Liturgisches Gerät"]}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00085","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Behälter","fi":"säilytysastiat","sv":"behållare","pt":"recepientes","en":"containers (receptacles)","hr":"spremnik."}}],"inCollections":["http://partage.vocnet.org/IndexingConcepts","http://partage.vocnet.org/PPRefiningObjectType"],"exactMatch":["http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300083005"],"inSchemes":["http://partage.vocnet.org/Objects"],"vocabulary":{"name":"partageplus","version":"0"}}}

Functional design: the form is based on function, construction and material. Characteristics are a division of constructive and functional elements, respect for the material used, restricted and subordinate use of ornament that accentuates the construction. Ornaments are often nature-based and reduced to mathematical principles (geometrical/linear). Inspired by the wish to make well-designed objects available to large groups in society, these socially-engaged artists welcomed the machine into the production process. This style flourished in Amsterdam."},"broader":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00375","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"Nieuwe Kunst"}}],"broaderTransitive":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00375","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"Nieuwe Kunst"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00353","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"Art Nouveau"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00349","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"European"}}],"inCollections":["http://partage.vocnet.org/IndexingConcepts","http://partage.vocnet.org/PPArtNouveauStyle"],"inSchemes":["http://partage.vocnet.org/StylesAndPeriods"],"vocabulary":{"name":"partageplus","version":"0"}}}

{"semantic":{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00249","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Glasmalerei (Glasfenster)","no":"blyglass","sv":"blyglas","fi":"lasimaalaus","pt":"vitral","en":"stained glass","hr":"vitraji","it":"vetri colorati","fr":"vitrail","hu":"ólomüveg","es":"vidriera de colores","cs":"vitráž","sl":"vitraži","pl":"witraże","ca":"vitrall","nl":"gebrandschilderd glas"},"altLabel":{"de":["Buntglas","Farbglas"],"en":["stained glass (visual works)"]},"scopeNote":{"en":"Refers to works made of colored glass, generally in the form of a window, autonomous panel, or lampshade, in which the design is meant to be observed through refracted light and its effect is greatly dependent on the quality of the light. The stages of manufacture were described in a manual written in the early twelfth century by the monk Theophilus and the process has hardly changed since then. The window or other item is made by cutting pieces of colored glass based on a full-scale cartoon and holding the pieces together by strips of lead. Details may be painted on the surface of the pieces of glass and fired in a kiln before piecing the glass together. The method of weatherproofing and fixing the glass in a window is often highly decorative and forms an important element of the design. The highest achievements in stained glass are thought to be those of the Gothic era in Europe and those of the Gothic Revival of the nineteenth century."},"broader":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00044","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"no":"maleri","de":"Gemälde","fi":"maalaukset","sv":"målningar","pt":"pintura","en":"paintings","hr":"slikarstvo","it":"dipinti","fr":"peinture","hu":"festmény","es":"pintura","cs":"malba","sl":"slike","pl":"obrazy","nl":"schilderingen","ca":"pintura"},"altLabel":{"de":["Malerei"],"pt":["pinturas"],"en":["paintings (visual works)"],"es":["pinturas"]}}],"broaderTransitive":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00044","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"no":"maleri","de":"Gemälde","fi":"maalaukset","sv":"målningar","pt":"pintura","en":"paintings","hr":"slikarstvo","it":"dipinti","fr":"peinture","hu":"festmény","es":"pintura","cs":"malba","sl":"slike","pl":"obrazy","nl":"schilderingen","ca":"pintura"},"altLabel":{"de":["Malerei"],"pt":["pinturas"],"en":["paintings (visual works)"],"es":["pinturas"]}}],"inCollections":["http://partage.vocnet.org/IndexingConcepts","http://partage.vocnet.org/PPObjectType"],"exactMatch":["http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300263722"],"inSchemes":["http://partage.vocnet.org/Objects","http://partage.vocnet.org/MicroObjectTypes"],"vocabulary":{"name":"partageplus","version":"0"}}}

Dolls are commonly in the form of a baby or woman, often with changeable clothes; they may have moveable arms and legs. Doll may be made of cloth (rag dolls), wood, clay, porcelain, wax, paper, plastic, celluloid, corn husks, or other materials. Dolls may also be figurines used for ceremonial, religious, or decorative purposes. Archaeological evidence suggests that dolls were the first playthings; they have been found in Babylonian and Egyptian tombs from ca. 3000 BCE. {"semantic":{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00364","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"Glasgow style"},"scopeNote":{"en":"Scottish variation of Art Nouveau that originated at the Glasgow School of Art and flourished from ca. 1890 to ca. 1920. Chief among its proponents are Charles Rennie Mackintosh, Herbert MacNair and the sisters, Frances and Margaret MacDonald. When Francis H. Newbery (1853\\u20131946) became director of the Glasgow School in 1885, his teachings were influenced by the Arts and Crafts Movement that stressed an art that combined functionalism with beauty while encouraging individuality and experimentation among its students. The journal \\u201cThe Hobby Horse\\u201d (begun in spring 1884), expressed a desire for the unification of old and new and a harmonious relationship between abstract lines and masses. The style was further developed through the increasing popularity of Celtic revivalism taking root in Glasgow at the time. The style begins to dissipate with the coming of World War I."},"broader":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00353","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"Art Nouveau"}}],"broaderTransitive":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00353","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"Art Nouveau"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00349","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"European"}}],"inCollections":["http://partage.vocnet.org/IndexingConcepts","http://partage.vocnet.org/PPArtNouveauStyle"],"exactMatch":["http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300375728"],"inSchemes":["http://partage.vocnet.org/StylesAndPeriods"],"vocabulary":{"name":"partageplus","version":"0"}}}

Pure calcite marble is white, but impurities produce a wide variety of coloring and patterns. It is finely grained and polishes to a smooth, high gloss. It is used primarily for statuary and buildings. Marble has been quarried from sites around the world since at least the 7th century BCE. The term can also refer more broadly to any crystallized carbonate rock, including true marble and certain types of limestone, that will take a polish and can be used for architectural and ornamental purposes."},"broader":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00517","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"metamorphic rock"}}],"broaderTransitive":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00517","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"metamorphic rock"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00518","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"rock"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00229","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"materials (matter)"}}],"inCollections":["http://partage.vocnet.org/IndexingConcepts","http://partage.vocnet.org/PPMaterial"],"exactMatch":["http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300011443"],"inSchemes":["http://partage.vocnet.org/Materials"],"vocabulary":{"name":"partageplus","version":"0"}}}

{"semantic":{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00890","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Stereophotographie","fi":"stereokuvat","sv":"stereoskopiska fotografier","pt":"fotografia estereostópica","en":"stereoscopic photographs","hr":"stereoskopska fotografija"},"altLabel":{"de":["Stereofotografie"]},"scopeNote":{"en":"Refers to double pictures of the same scene that produce the effect of three dimensionality when viewed through a stereoscope. They were first envisioned in 1832 by the English physicist Charles Wheatstone, who described this as a uniquely photographic art form, since a draftsman could not draw two scenes in exact perspective from viewpoints separated only 2 1\\/2 inches, which is the normal distance between human eyes necessary for the three-dimensional effect. Wheatstone's mirror stereoscope was not practical for use with photographs, and the invention was not popular until the 1850s, when Sir David Brewster, a Scottish scientist, designed a simpler viewing instrument. The introduction of the collodion process, which simplified exposure and printing techniques, allowed three-dimensional photographs to become a popular craze. They may be daguerreotypes, negatives, or other forms of photographs. For images in the form of photographic prints on cards, use the more specific term \"stereographs.\""},"broader":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00419","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Fotografie","no":"fotografi","fi":"valokuvat","sv":"fotografier","pt":"fotografia","en":"photographs","hr":"fotografije","it":"fotografie","fr":"photographie","hu":"fénykép","es":"fotografías","cs":"fotografie","sl":"fotografije","pl":"fotografie","ca":"fotografies","nl":"foto's"},"altLabel":{"de":["Fotos","Fotografien","Photographien","Photographie"],"pt":["fotografias"]}}],"broaderTransitive":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00419","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Fotografie","no":"fotografi","fi":"valokuvat","sv":"fotografier","pt":"fotografia","en":"photographs","hr":"fotografije","it":"fotografie","fr":"photographie","hu":"fénykép","es":"fotografías","cs":"fotografie","sl":"fotografije","pl":"fotografie","ca":"fotografies","nl":"foto's"},"altLabel":{"de":["Fotos","Fotografien","Photographien","Photographie"],"pt":["fotografias"]}}],"inCollections":["http://partage.vocnet.org/IndexingConcepts","http://partage.vocnet.org/PPRefiningObjectType"],"exactMatch":["http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300162872"],"inSchemes":["http://partage.vocnet.org/Objects"],"vocabulary":{"name":"partageplus","version":"0"}}}

It was the first metal used by humans, probably from about 8000 BCE, in the regions of Mesopotamia and India. By about 3800 BCE copper was made into bronze for weapons and knives. Today, copper is one of the most widely used metals because it has high electrical and thermal conductivity, can be easily fabricated, is ductile and polishes well. In moist air, copper forms a protective green film of basic carbonate. Metallic copper combines well with other metals to form alloys, most commonly brass and bronze. Copper and its alloys are used for wire, electrical devices, pipes, cooking vessels, ammunition, ornamental trim, roofing, grillwork, coins, musical instruments, jewelry, and sculptures."},"broader":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00265","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"nonferrous metal"}}],"broaderTransitive":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00265","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"nonferrous metal"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00259","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Metall","sv":"metall","fi":"metalli","pt":"metal","en":"metal","hr":"metal"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00229","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"materials (matter)"}}],"inCollections":["http://partage.vocnet.org/IndexingConcepts","http://partage.vocnet.org/PPMaterial"],"exactMatch":["http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300011020"],"inSchemes":["http://partage.vocnet.org/Materials"],"vocabulary":{"name":"partageplus","version":"0"}}}

{"semantic":{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part01223","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Rosenholz","en":"rosewood (wood)"},"scopeNote":{"en":"Wood from several tropical trees of the genus Dalbergia, all having a dark red or purplish color streaked and variegated with black. Rosewood timber produces a rose-like smell when cut. The wood has a fine grain, smooth texture, and polishes to a high gloss, but because of its resinous nature is difficult to work. It is used for cabinets, musical instruments, piano cases, and veneer. It was popular during the late 18th and early 19th centuries. It is still used to fashion xylophone bars, but waning supplies restrict its use. Only around 15 of the species in the large genus Dalbergia yield rosewood."},"broader":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00606","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"hardwood"}}],"broaderTransitive":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00606","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"hardwood"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00295","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Holz","sv":"trä","fi":"puu","pt":"madeira","en":"wood","hr":"drvo"},"altLabel":{"en":["wood (plant material)"]}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00297","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"plant material"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00229","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"materials (matter)"}}],"inCollections":["http://partage.vocnet.org/IndexingConcepts","http://partage.vocnet.org/PPMaterial"],"exactMatch":["http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300012424"],"inSchemes":["http://partage.vocnet.org/Materials"],"vocabulary":{"name":"partageplus","version":"0"}}}

{"semantic":{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00041","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Skulptur","no":"skulptur","sv":"skulpturer","fi":"veistokset","pt":"escultura","en":"sculpture","hr":"skulpture","it":"scultura","fr":"sculpture","hu":"szobrászat","es":"escultura","cs":"sochařství","sl":"skulpture","pl":"rzeźba","nl":"beeldhouwwerken","ca":"escultura"},"altLabel":{"de":["Plastik"],"en":["sculpture (visual work)"],"sl":["kipi"]},"scopeNote":{"en":"Three-dimensional works of art in which images and forms are produced in relief, in intaglio, or in the round. The term refers particularly to art works created by carving or engraving a hard material, by molding or casting a malleable material (which usually then hardens), or by assembling parts to create a three-dimensional object. It is typically used to refer to large or medium-sized objects made of stone, wood, bronze, or another metal. Small objects are typically referred to as \"carvings\" or another appropriate term. \"Sculpture\" refers to works that represent tangible beings, objects, or groups of objects, or are abstract works that have defined edges and boundaries and can be measured. Silver is widely distributed throughout the world, occurring rarely as metallic silver (in Peru, Norway) but more often as silver-gold alloys and silver ore. Today silver is obtained as a byproduct in the refinement of gold, lead, copper, or zinc ores. Silver was smelted from the ore galena as early as 3800 BCE. {"semantic":{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00912","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Mahagoni","sv":"mahogny","fi":"mahonki","pt":"mogno","en":"mahogany","hr":"mahagonij"},"scopeNote":{"en":"Refers to the wood of trees of the genus Swietenia, found in tropical climates, primarily in Mexico, Cuba, Central America, and the West Indies. It varies in color from yellow to a rich red brown, and is valued in furniture-making and sculpture-carving because it is hard, fine-grained, and takes a high polish. Mahogany has a fine, straight grain that takes a high polish. It is dimensionally stable and does not shrink, warp, or swell. The durable, dark reddish-brown wood was imported to Europe in the 18th century where it became popular for furniture, paneling and veneer. Ammonia brings out a rich, red color in mahogany wood. Mahogany is frequently attacked by pinhole borer beetles. Many woods of similar colors have also been called mahoganies, but usually do not have rich color or fine cutting characteristics of the true mahogany wood. However, the related African genus Khaya produces a similar wood. Mahogany was used by Chippendale, Hepplewhite, and the Adam brothers for high quality furniture."},"broader":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00606","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"hardwood"}}],"broaderTransitive":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00606","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"hardwood"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00295","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Holz","sv":"trä","fi":"puu","pt":"madeira","en":"wood","hr":"drvo"},"altLabel":{"en":["wood (plant material)"]}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00297","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"plant material"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00229","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"materials (matter)"}}],"inCollections":["http://partage.vocnet.org/IndexingConcepts","http://partage.vocnet.org/PPMaterial"],"exactMatch":["http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300012221"],"inSchemes":["http://partage.vocnet.org/Materials"],"vocabulary":{"name":"partageplus","version":"0"}}}

Tapestries are characterized by decoration that may include ornamental or pictorial subjects; they often have details that are painted or embroidered. They are usually of wool and hand-woven on a tapestry loom by a process that differs from cloth-weaving in that the weft travels only to the warp at the edge of a particular color or pattern in the design, rather traveling from edge to edge of the entire piece of fabric. Various techniques are used in mixing and overlaying colors to create shading and patterns. {"semantic":{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00276","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Blei","sv":"bly","fi":"lyijy","pt":"chumbo","en":"lead","hr":"olovo"},"altLabel":{"en":["lead (metal)"]},"scopeNote":{"en":"Pure metallic element having symbol Pb and atomic number 82; soft, dense ductile metal of a dull gray color, shiny when freshly cut, occuring naturally most often as a sulfide in the mineral galena. Other lead minerals include anglesite (lead sulfate) and cerussite (lead carbonate). Native metallic lead was found and used from about 3600-2600 BCE when the technique for obtaining lead from roasting the sulfide ore (galena) was discovered. Lead was used to make small cast items such as coins and statuettes, plumbing pipes, spires, statues, cisterns, gargoyles, pigments (lead white, litharge, orange mineral, etc.), as a component in pottery glazes, for roofing, flashing, stained glass windows, as a soft solder, and as radiation shielding."},"broader":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00265","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"nonferrous metal"}}],"broaderTransitive":[{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00265","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"nonferrous metal"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00259","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"de":"Metall","sv":"metall","fi":"metalli","pt":"metal","en":"metal","hr":"metal"}},{"uri":"http://partage.vocnet.org/part00229","type":"http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept","prefLabel":{"en":"materials (matter)"}}],"inCollections":["http://partage.vocnet.org/IndexingConcepts","http://partage.vocnet.org/PPMaterial"],"exactMatch":["http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300011022"],"inSchemes":["http://partage.vocnet.org/Materials"],"vocabulary":{"name":"partageplus","version":"0"}}}
